{
  "query": "What are the effects on butterfly and moth communities of opening up forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning?",
  "relevant_summary": "Forest canopy opening through clearing, coppicing, and thinning has different effects on butterfly and moth communities. Clearing or opening patches in forests generally benefits butterflies but can negatively impact moths. Studies found that cleared patches in forests had greater species richness of butterflies but lower species richness of moths than unmanaged patches or closed canopy forest (action 3938). Butterfly abundance was higher in cleared patches that were also managed with coppicing and grazing compared to before management or unmanaged areas, though butterfly abundance declined over the first three years after clearing (action 3938). Larger cleared patches supported higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than undisturbed forest, while smaller patches did not show this benefit (action 3938). For moths, wider woodland rides had lower abundance of macro-moths than standard width rides or mature forest (action 3938). Coppicing woodland shows positive effects for butterflies, with coppiced woodland having greater species richness of butterflies than unmanaged woodland, and higher abundance of butterflies generally and heath fritillary specifically (action 3939). However, coppiced woodland had lower species richness and abundance of macro-moths than mature forest (action 3939). The timing of coppicing matters, with woodland coppiced 2-4 years ago showing greater butterfly abundance than woodland coppiced 5-11 or >15 years ago (action 3939). Thinning trees within forests combined with other management practices like prescribed burning or mulching resulted in greater species richness and abundance of butterflies compared to unmanaged woodland or before management (action 3940). Studies found that partially-cleared forest plots had higher butterfly but lower moth species richness than closed-canopy forest plots (action 3940). When comparing different harvesting methods, thinning resulted in higher macro-moth species richness than patch-cutting or clearcutting, with richness similar to unharvested forest (action 3868).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3938",
    "3940",
    "3939",
    "3868"
  ]
}

