{
  "query": "What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence on the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation and captive-release shows mixed results with generally low long-term survival rates. A review across the UK and Ireland found that only 25% of translocated and captive-bred butterfly populations survived for at least three years, with 38% dying out within that time period, and only 8% known to have survived for more than 10 years (Action 3909, 3914). \n\nFor translocation within former range, eight studies reported that translocated populations of adult butterflies persisted for 2-12 years and increased in abundance, while three studies found that some translocated populations persisted for 1-49 years and colonized new sites, but other populations died out within 0-7 years (Action 3909). Specifically for large copper, translocated populations survived for up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required supplementation by further releases (Action 3909).\n\nFor captive-bred releases, six studies reported that populations persisted for 2-28 years and increased in abundance, while two studies found that captive-bred populations died out one, two, or 12 years after release, or required further releases to survive (Action 3914). One study found that only three of 10 captive-bred barberry carpet moth populations established, with at least one persisting for five years (Action 3914).\n\nFor translocation outside known range, two of three studies reported that populations persisted and increased in abundance over eight and 28 years, while one population died out within one year (Action 3911). \n\nCaptive breeding programs showed that populations could be successfully maintained, with some species reared for 12 generations or more than 25 years in captivity (Action 3916). However, survival rates varied significantly depending on rearing conditions, with factors such as density, temperature, and ant species affecting success rates (Action 3916).",
