  "relevant_summary": "Restoring grassland from arable land shows positive benefits for butterfly communities, with several studies demonstrating that 4-5-year-old created grasslands and abandoned cropland had greater species richness of butterflies, burnet moths and all moths than conventionally managed grassland or cultivated farms (Action 3929). Grasslands restored from arable land by sowing grasses, legumes and other non-woody, broadleaved plants had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than grasslands established with grass-only mixes or less competitive species (Action 3929). Over 10 years after restoration, restored grassland from arable land had higher abundance of moths than conventional grassland and similar abundance to semi-natural grasslands, though abundance did not increase with time since restoration (Action 3929).\n\nIn contrast, restoration outcomes from abandoned meadows show more variable results. Semi-natural grasslands restored by scrub clearance and reintroduction of grazing or mowing had different butterfly communities to existing species-rich grasslands and did not become more similar over time (Action 3955). Some studies found that semi-natural grasslands restored by cattle grazing had lower species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than unrestored and continuously managed grasslands (Action 3955). However, grasslands restored by scrub clearing showed higher density of blue-spot hairstreak eggs and egg batches than unrestored or continuously managed grasslands (Action 3955).\n\nFor grasslands where management ceased on existing meadows, effects varied by time since abandonment. Grasslands abandoned for 3-13 years had similar species richness of butterflies and burnet moths to grasslands managed by mowing, while grasslands abandoned for more than 50 years had lower species richness than annually mowed grasslands (Action 3957). Grasslands abandoned for 5-20 years showed mixed abundance patterns depending on butterfly species compared to grazed grasslands (Action 3956), and after abandonment, butterfly communities became dominated by generalist species with fewer generations per year (Action 3956).",
