{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and negative impacts of using prescribed fire in forest ecosystems for butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on documented research, prescribed fire in forest ecosystems shows both beneficial and negative impacts on butterfly and moth populations. \n\nBenefits documented include: Three of four studies found that coniferous forest restored 1-2 years ago by burning (in combination with thinning) or burned once within the last 20 years had higher species richness of butterflies than unburned forest (Action 3877). Two studies found that pine forest restored 1-2 years ago by burning (in combination with thinning) had higher abundance of butterflies than unburned forest (Action 3877). Leaving unburned patches during prescribed burning showed positive effects, with Karner blue butterfly abundance increasing over 2-3 years in oak savannas and prairies where unburned patches were left, and six out of nine specialist butterfly species were more abundant in pine barrens and prairies with unburned areas compared to sites without unburned areas (Action 3879). Karner blue butterflies were documented using all 11 unburned patches surveyed within oak savannas and prairies managed by burning (Action 3879).\n\nNegative impacts documented include: One study found that mixed forest and shrubland sites burned the year before had similar butterfly species richness to unburned sites, showing no benefit (Action 3877). One study reported that in the spring after selective burning of eucalyptus forest there were fewer Eltham copper caterpillars than before (Action 3877). Management with late season burning did not increase caterpillar abundance, while early season burning or no burning for 2-5 years did increase abundance (Action 3878). \n\nThe timing of prescribed burning appears important, as one study found that early season burning or no burning for 2-5 years increased caterpillar abundance in tropical savanna and floodplain, but late season burning did not (Action 3878).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3877",
