{
  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of restoring habitats after mining and quarrying activities for butterfly and moth conservation?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence regarding habitat restoration after mining and quarrying activities for butterfly and moth conservation is limited but provides some important insights. Four studies have specifically evaluated the effects of restoring or creating new habitats after mining and quarrying on butterflies and moths, conducted in the Czech Republic, UK, and New Zealand (action 3862). Key findings include: technically restored quarries had lower species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than quarries left to restore naturally, and flattened spoil heaps had lower species richness of moths than unflattened spoil heaps (action 3862). However, one Czech study found that 15% of 380 invertebrate species (including 208 moth species) were only found on flattened spoil heaps, compared to 30% which were only found on unflattened heaps, suggesting both restoration approaches support unique species communities (action 3862). Positive restoration outcomes were also documented: a peat bog restored after mining in New Zealand supported similar density and size of Fred the thread moth caterpillars to undisturbed bogs, and on slate waste tips in the UK, trees with applied fertilizer had similar abundance of caterpillars to unfertilized trees (action 3862). Notably, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of protecting or restoring brownfield or ex-industrial sites specifically for butterflies and moths (action 3835).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3862",
    "3835"
  ]
}

