{
  "query": "Over what timescales have butterfly populations been observed to respond to woodland management practices like coppicing and clearing in the UK?",
  "relevant_summary": "Butterfly populations in the UK have been observed to respond to woodland management practices across several different timescales. For coppicing management, one study found that woodland coppiced two years ago had a greater species richness of butterflies than woodland coppiced >15 years ago (action 3939). The abundance of butterflies generally, heath fritillary specifically, and eastern eggar moth and scarce fritillary caterpillar webs, was higher in woodland coppiced two, two\u2013four, five\u2013seven or 12\u201315 years ago than in woodland coppiced 5\u201311 or >15 years ago (action 3939). Pearl-bordered fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary populations were more likely to persist for up to 20 years in coppiced woodland than in mature conifer woodland (action 3939). For clearing management, one study found that patches cleared 2\u20134 years ago had a greater abundance of heath fritillary than patches cleared 7\u201311 years ago or patches in their first year after clearance (action 3938). The species richness of butterflies declined over the first three years after clearing, and the abundance of butterflies also declined over the first three years after clearing (action 3938). Pearl-bordered fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary populations were more likely to persist for up to 20 years in woodlands with larger areas of young plantations or coppicing than in mature coniferous or deciduous woodland (action 3941).",
